  "prompt": "Is using \"hairs\" instead of \"hair\" grammatically incorrect?",
  "response": "Using \"hairs\" instead of \"hair\" is not grammatically incorrect, but it depends on the context. The word \"hair\" is typically used as an uncountable noun to refer to the collective mass of hair on a person's head (e.g., \"Her hair is long and curly\"). However, \"hairs\" can be used as a countable noun when referring to individual strands, especially in specific contexts or scientific discussions (e.g., \"There are three hairs on the pillow\").\n\nIn everyday language, \"hair\" is more commonly used to describe the whole as a mass noun, but if you need to specify individual strands, \"hairs\" is acceptable.",
